        <li parentName="ul">{`You know how to `}<a parentName="li" {...{
            "href": "/guides/advanced/parsing-csv-logs-with-lua/"
          }}>{`parse CSV logs with Lua`}</a>{`.`}</li>
      </ul>
    </Assumptions>
    <p>{`The `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/guides/advanced/parsing-csv-logs-with-lua/"
      }}>{`guide on parsing CSV logs with Lua`}</a>{` describes how to parse CSV logs containing
values which do not contain line breaks. However, according to `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4180"
      }}>{`RFC 4180`}</a>{`, CSV values enclosed in double
quotes can contain line breaks. This means that parsing arbitrary CSV logs requires handling such lines breaks
correctly.`}</p>
    <p>{`For general case, this cannot be accomplished using the
`}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/docs/reference/sources/file/#multiline"
      }}><inlineCode parentName="a">{`multiline`}</inlineCode>{` option of the `}<inlineCode parentName="a">{`file`}</inlineCode>{` source`}</a>{` because it uses regular expressions
for delimiting lines, and for the given use case a full-fledged CSV parser is necessary.`}</p>
    {
      /*
          THIS FILE IS AUTOGENERATED!
